tion. He shows how the new architecture came unexpectedly to be invented in the Paris region around 1140 and follows its history—in the great cathedrals of northern France and dozens of other key buildings—to the end of the thirteenth century, when profound changes occurred in the whole fabric of medieval civilization. Rich illustrations, including comprehensive maps, enhance the text and themselves constitute an exceptionally valuable documenation. Despite its evident scholarly intention, this book is not meant for specialists alone, but is conceived as a progressive infiltration into the complexities of history at work, revealing its unpredictable vitality to the uninitiated curious mind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArchitecture, GothiczFrance. 0aChurch architecturezFrance. 4aarchitecture. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory. 4athe arts. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aadventure of imagination.  aart and architecture.  acomprehensive maps.  aeleven forty.  aend of 13th century.  afrance.  agothic architecture.  agreat cathedrals of northern france.  ahandling space and light.  ahistory of gothic architecture.  aillustrated.  ainvented in paris region.  amechanics of stone construction.  amedieval european civilization.  aradical technical advances.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052090787440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520907874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520907874/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles